        "body": "<p>The standard Java api does not have a variable-size array of primitives (other than reference types). There are third-party libraries that do provide this functionality (<a href=\"http://trove.starlight-systems.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">GNU trove<\/a> is widely used; see <a href=\"http://java.dzone.com/articles/java-collections-%E2%80%93-are-there\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> for a list good-quality libraries), or you can build your own.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you don't mind the overhead of boxing/unboxing, you can use an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT<\/strong> Looking at the code you posted, the only thing wrong I see is that you are declaring <code>ints<\/code> as both an <code>Integer[]<\/code> and as a <code>static List&lt;Integer&gt;<\/code>. You can't declare the same variable twice. Get rid of the <code>Integer[]<\/code> declaration and the rest of your code looks like it should behave properly (at least the part about adding integer values to a variable-size list; I don't know anything about your logic).<\/p>\n",
